+VSP (Virtual Service Provider) interface that has had support in the Hyper-V
+drivers for a decade.
+
+In the case the device does not support encrypted memory, the paravisor
+provides bounce-buffering, and although the data is not encrypted, the backing
+pages aren't mapped into the host partition through SLAT. While not impossible,
+it becomes much more difficult for the host partition to exfiltrate the data
+than it would be with a conventional VMBus connection where the host partition
+has direct access to the memory used for communication.
+
+Here is the data flow for a conventional VMBus connection (`C` stands for the
+client or VSC, `S` for the server or VSP, the `DEVICE` is a physical one, might
+be with multiple virtual functions)::
+
+  +---- GUEST ----+       +----- DEVICE ----+        +----- HOST -----+
+  |               |       |                 |        |                |
+  |               |       |                 |        |                |
+  |               |       |                 ==========                |
+  |               |       |                 |        |                |
+  |               |       |                 |        |                |
+  |               |       |                 |        |                |
+  +----- C -------+       +-----------------+        +------- S ------+
+         ||                                                   ||
+         ||                                                   ||
+  +------||------------------ VMBus --------------------------||------+
+  |                     Interrupts, MMIO                              |
+  +-------------------------------------------------------------------+
+
+and the Confidential VMBus connection::
+
+  +---- GUEST --------------- VTL0 ------+               +-- DEVICE --+
+  |                                      |               |            |
+  | +- PARAVISOR --------- VTL2 -----+   |               |            |
+  | |     +-- VMBus Relay ------+    ====+================            |
+  | |     |   Interrupts, MMIO  |    |   |               |            |
+  | |     +-------- S ----------+    |   |               +------------+
+  | |               ||               |   |
+  | +---------+     ||               |   |
+  | |  Linux  |     ||    OpenHCL    |   |
+  | |  kernel |     ||               |   |
+  | +---- C --+-----||---------------+   |
+  |       ||        ||                   |
+  +-------++------- C -------------------+               +------------+
+          ||                                             |    HOST    |
+          ||                                             +---- S -----+
+  +-------||----------------- VMBus ---------------------------||-----+
+  |                     Interrupts, MMIO                              |
+  +-------------------------------------------------------------------+
+

commit 812f223fe9be03dc22abb85240b6f075135d2386
Author: Thomas Weißschuh <thomas.weissschuh@linutronix.de>
Date:   Fri Sep 26 16:26:58 2025 +0200

    tools/nolibc: handle NULL wstatus argument to waitpid()
    
    wstatus is allowed to be NULL. Avoid a segmentation fault in this case.
    
    Fixes: 0c89abf5ab3f ("tools/nolibc: implement waitpid() in terms of waitid()")

index 4e66e1f7a03e4..9d9319ba92cbd 100644
--- a/tools/include/nolibc/sys/wait.h
+++ b/tools/include/nolibc/sys/wait.h
@@ -65,23 +65,29 @@ pid_t waitpid(pid_t pid, int *status, int options)
 
 	switch (info.si_code) {
 	case 0:
-		*status = 0;
+		if (status)
+			*status = 0;
 		break;
 	case CLD_EXITED:
-		*status = (info.si_status & 0xff) << 8;
+		if (status)
+			*status = (info.si_status & 0xff) << 8;
 		break;
 	case CLD_KILLED:
-		*status = info.si_status & 0x7f;
+		if (status)
+			*status = info.si_status & 0x7f;
 		break;
 	case CLD_DUMPED:
-		*status = (info.si_status & 0x7f) | 0x80;
+		if (status)
+			*status = (info.si_status & 0x7f) | 0x80;
 		break;
 	case CLD_STOPPED:
 	case CLD_TRAPPED:
-		*status = (info.si_status << 8) + 0x7f;
+		if (status)
+			*status = (info.si_status << 8) + 0x7f;
 		break;
 	case CLD_CONTINUED:
-		*status = 0xffff;
+		if (status)
+			*status = 0xffff;
 		break;
 	default:
 		return -1;

args.thoughts: QEMU now mounts the ext4 root on /dev/vda1 successfully, but panics because it cannot execute the requested init (/sbin/init) with error -8 (ENOEXEC). This strongly suggests missing binary format support for the init binary (likely ELF and/or shebang script support), which aligns with latest config having CONFIG_BINFMT_ELF disabled and BINFMT_SCRIPT absent. Minimal fix is to restore CONFIG_BINFMT_ELF and CONFIG_BINFMT_SCRIPT to allow executing /sbin/init or its wrapper script.
args.observations: QEMU log: EXT4 root mounted, devtmpfs mounted, then `Run /sbin/init as init process` followed by `Kernel panic - not syncing: Requested init /sbin/init failed (error -8).` Latest config: CONFIG_BINFMT_ELF=False, CONFIG_UEVENT_HELPER=False, and CONFIG_BINFMT_SCRIPT missing. Base config has CONFIG_BINFMT_ELF=y and CONFIG_BINFMT_SCRIPT=y. Build log shows successful kernel build with GZIP bzImage.
args.actions: Searched QEMU log for panic lines and virtio/root mount status; confirmed rootfs mounts and init execution fails with -8. Cross-checked base vs latest configs for binfmt/initrd/devtmpfs; identified BINFMT_ELF/BINFMT_SCRIPT regression. Applied minimal config changes: define CONFIG_BINFMT_ELF and CONFIG_BINFMT_SCRIPT; ran apply_and_test.
args.next_steps: Inspect the updated QEMU log from this run to see whether init now starts or if a different error appears (e.g., -2 ENOENT for missing /sbin/init, missing devpts/tmpfs, or userspace requiring other kernel features). If still error -8, check whether /sbin/init is an interpreter script requiring CONFIG_BINFMT_SCRIPT or whether it is a dynamically linked ELF needing CONFIG_BINFMT_ELF plus compatible ABI; then add the minimal additional missing option(s) accordingly.
